'''Claude Frédéric-Armand Schaeffer''' (March 6, 1898 – August 25, 1982)<ref>Vercoutter, Jean. (1989). [https://www.persee.fr/doc/crai_0065-0536_1989_num_133_1_14707 ''Notice sur la vie et les travaux de Claude Schaeffer-Forrer, membre de l'Académie'']. ''[[Comptes rendus des séances de l'Académie des Inscriptions et Belles-Lettres]]''. 133 (1): 178-188.</ref><ref>[http://archaeology.about.com/od/sterms/g/schaeffercfa.htm Biography of Claude F. A. Schaeffer]</ref> was a [[French people|French]] [[Archaeology|archeologist]], born in Strasbourg, who led the [[France|French]] [[Excavation (archaeology)|excavation]] team that began working on the site of [[Ugarit]], the present day [[Ras Shamra]] in 1929, leading to the uncovering of the [[Ugarit#Ugaritic religion|Ugaritic religious texts]].<ref name="brit">http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/612669/Ugarit ; "Claude Schaeffer", in ''Je m'appelle [[Byblos]]'', [[Jean-Pierre Thiollet]], H & D, 2005, p.256-257.</ref>
He was curator for the Prehistoric and Gallo-Roman Museum, Strasbourg (1924–1933) and for the [[National Archaeological Museum (France)|Museum of National Antiquities, Saint-Germain-en-Laye]] (1933–1956).<ref>Anonymous. (1998). ''Claude-Frédéric-Armand Schaeffer''. In ''The New Encyclopaedia Britannica, Volume 10''. Encyclopaedia Britannica, Inc. p. 507</ref> Schaeffer was an advocate of [[catastrophism]]. He argued that on at least five occasions catastrophic events (such as earthquakes) had destroyed [[Bronze Age]] civilizations.<ref>Burton Brown, T. (1949). [https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/journal-of-hellenic-studies/article/stratigraphie-comparee-et-chronologie-de-lasie-occidentale-iiie-et-iie-millenaires-by-schaeffer-c-f-a-pp-xiii-653-pl-70-324-text-figs-1-map-london-oxford-university-press-1947-84s/67452919EEB79F0EF96F0ECC8C187FC2 ''Stratigraphie comparée et chronologie de l'Asie occidentale (IIIe et IIe millénaires) By C. F. A. Schaeffer'']. ''[[The Journal of Hellenic Studies]]'' 69: 114.</ref><ref>Palmer, Trevor. (2003). ''Perilous Planet Earth: Catastrophes and Catastrophism Through the Ages''. Cambridge University Press. pp. 120-121. {{ISBN|0-521-81928-8}}</ref>
